Because of payments made to all and sundry as compensation for
disruption.  Network Rail pays millions in compensation each year.

In BR days, this didn't happen.  IF BR's work on a station disrupted
BR's train services, BR didn't have to pay BR anything.  Trains were
either disrupted or cancelled for the duration of the work, people
just accepted it, and that was that.

Of course not one penny of the millions of pounds in compensation paid
to TOCs by Network Rail ever gets to the long suffering passengers.
TOCs pass on the disruption to their passengers, but keep the money.
It merely swells the TOCs' profits.
